The paper deals with modeling and analyzing different types of random network communications, including error control, rate, delay, and throughput. This suggests that the paper is likely to belong to the Information Theory (cs.IT) and Networking and Internet Architecture (cs.NI) sub-categories. Additionally, the paper proposes a novel protocol based on affine combinations of packets, which falls under the category of coding theory (cs.IT). The paper also uses matroid theory to model the network communications, which could potentially place it in the Discrete Mathematics (cs.DS) sub-category. Finally, the paper evaluates the performance of different network protocols, which could fall under the sub-categories of Social and Information Networks (cs.SI) and Computational Complexity (cs.CC).
